  "slug": "bara-brith",
  "title": "Bara brith",
  "subtitle": "Welsh tea loaf with dried fruit",
  "excerpt": "A dark, dense Welsh fruit loaf made without yeast or fat. Dried fruit soaks overnight in strong tea, which swells the sultanas and raisins and darkens the crumb. Sliced thick and spread with cold salted butter.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Florence White, Good Things in England (1932), bara brith documented as a Welsh regional speciality. The no-yeast tea-soaked version became the standard domestic recipe in the twentieth century, distinct from the older yeasted loaf baked at hearths and in bread ovens.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bara brith (literally 'speckled bread' in Welsh) is not a bread in any modern sense: no yeast, no fat, no shaping. The technique is ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "soaking the fruit",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpaeezzf0000dov4zvyv68fs"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " overnight in strong tea, then mixing the swollen fruit and its liquid with egg, flour, and spice. The result is a dense, dark loaf that slices cleanly and improves by the next day.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "ingredientsGroup",
            "attrs": {
              "title": null
            },
            "content": [
              {
